args:
Having rescued Leif, the party returns to the
landship. Leif suggests working together with
New Alberia, but Chelle's response is less than
positive. But when fiends attack, she finds
herself more open to bargaining, after which
the prince and his party engage the enemy.
All right, that'll do it for the fiends.\nAre you okay, Leif?
Your Highness?\nDid the princess also invite you here?
We haven't seen each other since we\nparted ways back in the capital, Leif.\nI hope you've been well.
You carried yourself splendidly in that\nbattle, Highness. Our time apart has\nseen you grow into a fine young man.
Well, we've been busy,\nso I had to learn fast.
Still, we should save our catching up\nuntil we're somewhere safer.
Eee hee hee! My, but that was a simply\nDELIGHTFUL bit of entertainment!
The beloved prince saves the infamous \nWhite Sparrows from danger and sparks\na heartfelt reunion in the process?
The members of my court were held in\nRAPT attention, let me tell you.
Then those fiends were YOUR doing,\nPrincess Chelle?!
What in the world were you thinking?!\nEven one of your standing must—
My, but aren't YOU the hot-blooded one!\nVice Captain Patia, is it not?
Oh, indeed I do. And honestly, I thought\nyou would have been most GLAD for the\nopportunity I provided...but it seems not.
Because I thought you enjoyed fighting!\nYou certainly seemed most eager to\ncross swords with Empress Zethia.
You said you would gladly give your life\nfor a chance to strike her, I believe?
I don't... How could you possibly...?!

Oh, curious little cats are always turning
their ears in your direction, I imagine.
That's why it's good practice to watch
what you say—and about whom.
Your Highness, I implore you not\nto make sport of my subordinates.

Oh? Well then, I beg your humble pardon!
Still, wouldn't you agree that someone
with the gall to threaten the royal family
be owed a lesson in respect?
I see that your disposition has made the\njourney to the present well intact.
Yes, how very unfortunate. But alas,\nI am as I was when I was your charge.
You never DID like me, did you?
Okay, whaaaaat is happening right now?
No matter; ancient history isn't worth the\ntime spent thinking on it. Come, Leif!\nWe have a party to attend.
I did not come here to revel, Princess.\nI should think you well aware of that.
Then why did you answer my invitation?

Such feigned ignorance ill suits you.
You know full well that your invitation
arrived at precisely the moment when
I resolved to depart the capital.
I presume your little ＂cats＂ have been\npaying mind to my movements for quite\nsome time.
I believe your invitation proves our aims\ntravel on a similar course.
I would hear exactly what these\n＂aims＂ of yours are, Sparrow.
I am a knight of Alberia, and a knight's\naim is ever to protect the royal family\nand deliver them from hardship.
...Even if said royal family member\nhas had their body possessed.
Let me tell you what has transpired of late.\nAfter the revival of the Dyrenell Empire,\nI remained steadfast in the capital.
It was a choice I made with reluctance,\nbut one I judged best for the sake of\nfinding a way to free Princess Zethia.
Which is why you've been pretending to\nsupport the Empire until now, I take it.\nSo did you find anything?

Unfortunately, I cannot say with certainty.
But in order to gain that certainty, it is
necessary to understand exactly what
is lurking inside Zethia's body.
And I believe that knowledge\nmay lie in Clave Loy'elune.
Er, and what IS Clave Loy'elune?
Hold on. Just what does this conversation\nhave to do with me?
I fear I have no real interest in that\nyounger sister of ours.
Oh man, this lady is ICE cold.
Zethia's state is the state of this nation.\nHow can that not hold your interest?
I won't deny this country is a key gala\nvenue for me, so I'm rather heartbroken\nto see what's been happening to it lately.
Then you should cooperate with us\nuntil we eliminate the tyranny\nof the Empire for good and all.
For it is currently a battle fought only by\nNew Alberia and {player_name}.
I think it is past time that the royal\nfamily cooperate with him and take\na stand against the Empire.
Please, Chelle, listen to him! He's right!
I want to save Zethia, but more than\nthat I want to salvage the happiness\nand prosperity of our people.
My, but that IS a pickle!
How can you do anything but offer your\naid, Princess Chelle? What possible\nreason could you have for refusal?
Because there is no advantage to MYSELF,\ndear Leif. And as such, I see no real need\nfor me to join this little cause of yours.
To be certain, if I WERE to cooperate,\nI would likely gain some small measure\nof military might in the process...
But are you aware of what THIS is?
Ooo! Ooo! I know! It's a jewel!
This, my excitable sylvan, is materium—\nan ancient substance that can be mined\nfrom the outskirts of Chanzelia.

It can hold almost impossible amounts
of pure mana, which can then be used in
whatever way the wielder desires.
It is an item beyond value.

Yes, materium made my city a source of
endless wealth. And with that wealth, I can
buy weapons or military might or whatever
I please...which means I do not need YOU.
If I were to cooperate with you people,\nthe eye of the Empire would turn to me.
How can I possibly host my galas in peace\nif I am constantly being hounded by the\nEmpire as you are, mmm?
Do you have any concept of how the\npeople of this kingdom are suffering\nunder the rule of the Empire?!
Your brother alone seeks to fight on\ntheir behalf, yet you would sit here\nand speak of base entertainment?!
I fear empathy always HAS been one\nof my brother's more pathetic traits.

Do you think the poor and desolate wish
to see the rich and powerful brought low?
To see their social betters eke out a
meager living in the muck as they do?
No! The masses do not want a leader\nwho suffers alongside them—they want\na leader who pulls them OUT of suffering!

The duty of a monarch is not to understand
the trials and tribulations of her people—
it is to lift them up so they might enjoy the
same splendid life of ease that she does!
The course you are on will not quiet the\nsuffering of a single soul, dear brother.\nIt will only make that suffering worse.
If you would call yourself a king, you need\nat least understand that much.
I hear what you're saying, Chelle,\nbut I think—
Hold that thought. ...Yes, Captain?\nWhat is it?
The landship is under siege by fiends,\nYour Highness—and there are even\nmore making their way to Chanzelia.
*sigh* It seems I may have tried TOO hard\nto make this a lively party. ...Very well,\nCaptain. What should we do about it?

I do not believe their current numbers
pose a significant threat to the Gran Fiore.
Additionally, the outer wall of the city
should hold them at bay there.
However, the small villages located\noutside the wall will likely be ravaged.
Oh my. What to do, what to do...?
Oh, but I have a SPLENDID idea!\nWhy don't all of YOU go out there and\ntake care of the nasty beasties for me?
If you do, it miiiight sway my opinion\nwhen it comes to cooperating with you.
You would seek to bargain with the lives\nof your own people?!

You CLEARLY did not pay attention to my
little speech earlier. If I can solve this
problem without getting my own hands
in the muck, so much the better.
I love me a good fight, but the thought of\ndoin' it for this lady makes my breakfast\nwanna hit the wall.
And yet if we refuse to help, it is the\npeople of the nearby villages who will\nsuffer for her selfishness.
Elly's right. We won't do this for my\nselfish sister—we'll do it for her people!
You REALLY ought to learn when to say\nthe quiet part of things quietly.
But very well! Go on and fight for whatever\nreason makes you happy—it will provide\nsplendid entertainment regardless.
Enough, Cleo. Your words will fall\non the deafest of ears in this place.
We should make haste, Your Highness.
Listen to me, everyone: Fighting for the\nsake of our people is the most worthy\nof causes, and we WILL protect them!
